subSubSection.paragraph:
At first, this species was misidentified by Montrouzier who described it under two endemic species:
Coccinella bicruciata
and
Verania artensis .
According to
Fauvel ( 1903 )
, who examined the type series,
Coelophora bicruciata (Montrouzier)
was a mixture of
Coelophora inaequalis
and
Micraspis frenata (Erichson)
specimens.
Verania artensis
was subsequently synonymized by
Chazeau ( 1978 )
.
Coelophora inaequalis
is widespread from both coasts to high altitude (> 1,000m ) on Grande Terre but also on Loyalty Islands and Isle of Pines. This species is widely distributed across Asia and the Pacific region ( Australia , Papua New Guinea , Vanuatu , Solomon Islands , Fiji Islands , Hawaii, Micronesia (Bonin, Marianna, Caroline, Wake , Marshall , Kiribati ), Cook Islands , Samoa , Wallis and Futuna , French Polynesia ); but also has been recorded from eastern North
America
. This is a polyphagous predator of hemipterous insects ( Aphididae, Coccomorpha ) from natural habitats to agricultural lands and disturbed areas. According to its geographic range and feeding biology, humans have probably spread this species during the first settlements. It is a well-known and largely promoted biocontrol agent against aphids (
Wang & Tsai 2001
).
